   "source": [
    "# 9. What do you mean by semi supervised learning?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "14fee0bf",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "🔹 What is Semi-Supervised Learning?\n",
    "📌 Definition\n",
    "\n",
    "Semi-supervised learning is a type of machine learning where:\n",
    "\n",
    "the model is trained using a small amount of labeled data and a large amount of unlabeled data.\n",
    "\n",
    "🧠 Core Idea\n",
    "\n",
    "In real life:\n",
    "\n",
    "Labeled data → expensive, time-consuming\n",
    "Unlabeled data → easily available\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 So we use both to improve model performance\n",
    "\n",
    "🔍 How it Works\n",
    "Start with a small labeled dataset\n",
    "Use it to train an initial model\n",
    "Use that model to predict labels for unlabeled data\n",
    "Use both labeled + predicted data to improve the model\n",
    "📊 Example\n",
    "Example: Email Classification (Spam Detection)\n",
    "100 emails → labeled (spam / not spam)\n",
    "10,000 emails → unlabeled\n",
    "Process:\n",
    "Train model on 100 labeled emails\n",
    "Predict labels for 10,000 emails\n",
    "Use confident predictions to retrain model\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 Model improves using unlabeled data\n",
    "\n",
    "🔹 Types of Learning (Comparison)\n",
    "Type\tData Used\n",
    "Supervised Learning\tOnly labeled data\n",
    "Unsupervised Learning\tOnly unlabeled data\n",
    "Semi-Supervised Learning\tBoth labeled + unlabeled\n",
    "🔹 Why Use Semi-Supervised Learning?\n",
    "1. Reduces Labeling Cost\n",
    "\n",
    "Labeling data manually is expensive (e.g., medical images)\n",
    "\n",
    "2. Improves Accuracy\n",
    "\n",
    "More data → better learning\n",
    "\n",
    "3. Uses Real-World Data Effectively\n",
    "\n",
    "Most real-world data is unlabeled\n",
    "\n",
    "🔹 Common Techniques\n",
    "1. Self-Training\n",
    "Model labels unlabeled data itself\n",
    "Retrains iteratively\n",
    "2. Co-Training\n",
    "Two models train each other\n",
    "3. Label Propagation\n",
    "Labels spread through similar data points\n",
    "4. Pseudo-Labeling\n",
    "Use predicted labels as true labels\n",
    "🔹 Real-World Examples\n",
    "Image classification with few labeled images\n",
    "Speech recognition\n",
    "Medical diagnosis\n",
    "Text classification\n",
    "Recommendation systems\n",
    "🔹 Beginner-Friendly Version\n",
    "\n",
    "Think like this:\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 You have:\n",
    "\n",
    "few questions with answers (labeled)\n",
    "many questions without answers (unlabeled)\n",
    "\n",
    "You:\n",
    "\n",
    "learn from answered ones\n",
    "guess answers for others\n",
    "improve learning\n",
    "🔹 Interview Answer (5 lines)\n",
    "\n",
    "Semi-supervised learning is a machine learning approach that uses both labeled and unlabeled data for training. Typically, a small amount of labeled data is combined with a large amount of unlabeled data. This approach helps improve model performance while reducing the cost of labeling. It is useful in real-world scenarios where labeled data is limited but unlabeled data is abundant. Techniques like self-training and pseudo-labeling are commonly used in semi-supervised learning.\n",
    "\n",
    "🔹 Advantages\n",
    "Reduces dependency on labeled data\n",
    "Better performance than supervised (with small data)\n",
    "Cost-efficient\n",
    "🔹 Disadvantages\n",
    "Risk of incorrect pseudo-labels\n",
    "Model bias may increase\n",
    "Needs careful tuning\n",
    "🔹 One-Line Memory Trick\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 Semi-supervised = little labeled + lots of unlabeled data\n",
    "\n",
    "🚀 Extra (Strong Interview Tip)\n",
    "\n",
    "You can add:\n",
    "\n",
    "“Semi-supervised learning lies between supervised and unsupervised learning and is very useful in domains where labeling data is expensive, such as healthcare and NLP.”"
   ]
  },
